you can't do systemctl --enable gnome-keyring-daemon ?

Actually, you cannot use systemctl enable for the gnome-keyring-daemon.

Here is why: gnome-keyring is a user-level service that needs to be tied to your specific login session and your graphical environment (X11 or Wayland/Hyprland). It isn't a standard background system service like a printer driver or a web server.

Why systemctl doesn't work here:
Session Binding: The keyring needs to know which "display" it belongs to so it can prompt you for a password visually.

DBus Integration: It relies on the User DBus session, which is initialized when you log in, not when the computer boots up.

No Service File: By default, gnome-keyring doesn't provide a standard .service file in /usr/lib/systemd/user/ that is designed to be "enabled" manually. It's designed to be triggered by a Desktop Environment or a manual exec command.

The Proper Arch Way (The "Clean" Method)
If you want to handle this more like a "system" service rather than just a line in hyprland.conf, you can use PAM (Pluggable Authentication Modules). This is the "gold standard" for Arch users because it unlocks your keyring automatically using your login password, so you don't get a second popup asking for a password when you open VS Code.

Edit your PAM login file:

Bash
sudo nano /etc/pam.d/login
Add these lines (add the auth line at the end of the auth section, and the session line at the end of the session section):

Plaintext
auth       optional     pam_gnome_keyring.so
session    optional     pam_gnome_keyring.so auto_start
Keep the line in hyprland.conf:
You still generally want the exec-once in your Hyprland config to ensure the environment variables are exported correctly to your Wayland session.

Pro-Tip: Check if it's working
After you restart and log in, run this in your terminal:

Bash
dbus-send --print-reply --dest=org.freedesktop.DBus /org/freedesktop/DBus org.freedesktop.DBus.ListNames | grep Secret
If you see org.freedesktop.secrets, you've won. VS Code will be happy.

