so with the PAM method, I actually need both?

Technically, yes, if you want a seamless experience.

It feels redundant, but they do two different jobs: PAM unlocks the vault, and the exec-once line makes sure the apps can find the door.

Here is the breakdown:
The PAM Method (/etc/pam.d/login):

Role: The "Locksmith."

What it does: When you type your password to log into your computer (via TTY or a Greeter like SDDM), PAM uses that same password to silently unlock your keyring.

Why you want it: Without this, your keyring stays "locked" even if the daemon is running. VS Code will start, but you'll get a frustrating popup asking for your login password again.

The Hyprland line (exec-once):

Role: The "Receptionist."

What it does: It starts the process and, more importantly, initializes the environment variables (like SSH_AUTH_SOCK) so that Wayland apps (like VS Code) know how to talk to the keyring.

Why you want it: It ensures that the "Secret Service" is actively listening for requests within your current Hyprland session.

The "I just want it to work" Strategy
If you want to keep your system clean, start with just the Hyprland line.

Try this first: Add exec-once = gnome-keyring-daemon --start --components=secrets to your hyprland.conf and restart.

The Litmus Test: Open VS Code.

If it works perfectly? Stop there.

If it works but asks for your password every single time you open it? Add the PAM lines.

One Final Warning (The Wayland "Gotcha")
Sometimes, even with both, VS Code can be a bit dense. If it still complains, it's usually because it can't find the "bus." You can force the issue by changing your exec-once line to this:

Ini, TOML
exec-once = dbus-update-activation-environment --systemd WAYLAND_DISPLAY XDG_CURRENT_DESKTOP
exec-once = gnome-keyring-daemon --start --components=secrets
This ensures the "room" is fully set up before the keyring daemon starts sitting in the chair.

