ok. now for the pam.d thing, don't I want it saved to dotfiles? using stow? how?

That is a very sharp observation. Since /etc/pam.d/login is a system-level file, it creates a bit of a dilemma for dotfile management.

The Problem with Stow and /etc
GNU Stow is designed to create symbolic links within your home directory (~). It generally shouldn't be used to manage /etc/ files because:

Permissions: Files in /etc must be owned by root. If you link to a file in your user folder, the system might refuse to use it for security reasons.

Privilege: Stow runs as your user, but writing to /etc requires sudo.

How to handle this (The "Best Practice" Way)
Since you can't easily "Stow" a system file, here are the three most common strategies used by Arch/Hyprland power users:

Option 1: The "Manual but Documented" Way (Recommended)
Keep a folder in your dotfiles called system-backups or root-configs. Copy your modified login file there.

Pro: You have a record of the change.

Con: If you move to a new machine, stow won't automatically apply it. You'll have to sudo cp it manually.

Option 2: The "Bootstrap Script" Way
Most people who use Stow also keep a setup.sh or install.sh script in their dotfiles. You can add a line to that script that injects the PAM configuration:

Bash
# Example line for a setup script
echo "auth optional pam_gnome_keyring.so" | sudo tee -a /etc/pam.d/login
Option 3: The "Systemd-Hacker" Way
If you really want to avoid touching /etc/pam.d/login, you can skip the PAM step entirely and use a Git/SSH askpass program or just deal with typing your password once per session when the keyring-daemon first starts.

My Recommendation
Don't try to force Stow to manage /etc. It usually leads to broken permissions and a system that won't let you log in.

Instead, do this:

Apply the fix manually: sudo nano /etc/pam.d/login.

Document it. Create a README.md or a notes.txt in your dotfiles repo.

Use your hyprland.conf for the heavy lifting. Since hyprland.conf is in your dotfiles and managed by Stow, putting the exec-once there is the "correct" way to handle the session start.

