what do you recommend

Since you're managing dotfiles with Stow and currently starting Hyprland manually from the TTY, I recommend moving to greetd with the tuigreet front-end.

Here is why this is the move for a "dotfiles-first" user:

Stow-Friendly: Unlike SDDM or GDM, which have heavy, messy configurations in /etc, greetd is minimal.

The "Keyring" Fix: Because it's a formal login manager, it handles the PAM (authentication) handshake correctly. This unlocks your gnome-keyring at the moment you type your password, so VS Code stops complaining immediately.

Modern & Lean: It feels like the TTY you're used to, but with a professional, riced-out look.

1. Install the Goods
Bash
sudo pacman -S greetd greetd-tuigreet
2. Configure it (The Dotfile Way)
Since the main config lives in /etc/greetd/config.toml, you can't easily Stow it, but you can create a one-liner command to point it to your start-hyprland script.

Edit /etc/greetd/config.toml (you'll need sudo) and set the command under [default_session]:

Ini, TOML
[default_session]
command = "tuigreet --time --remember --cmd start-hyprland"
user = "greeter"
--time: Shows a clock.

--remember: Remembers your username.

--cmd start-hyprland: This is the magic. It calls your existing script as soon as you log in.

3. Enable it
Now, stop "start-hyprland-ing" like a peasant:

Bash
sudo systemctl enable --now greetd
Why this beats the other options:
vs. SDDM: SDDM often tries to pull in half of the KDE Plasma desktop as dependencies. greetd is just a few megabytes.

vs. Ly: Ly is cool but notorious for being buggy with Wayland sessions and "ghosting" text on the screen.

vs. TTY: You get the same speed as the TTY, but your environment variables and keyring are initialized properly by the system, which is what VS Code is looking for.

The "Dotfiles" Win
In your dotfiles repo, I’d recommend keeping a folder called system/ where you store a copy of that config.toml. Even if you can't Stow it directly to /etc, you have it saved for your next install.

One final tip: If you go this route, you can keep your exec-once = gnome-keyring-daemon --start --components=secrets line in hyprland.conf. The combination of greetd (handling the password) and hyprland.conf (starting the daemon) is the bulletproof setup.

